The given pentagon doesn't have to be drawn accurately in order to solve the problem. Besides, the lengths satisfying the triangle inequality are sufficient to guarantee the existence of a triangle with those dimensions. With that being said, here's a diagram: <asy>
unitsize(0.4 cm);
pair A, B, C, D, E, I;
B = (0,0);
C = (13,0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc(B,5,0,180),arc(C,12,0,180));
I = (12,0);
E = (46/5, 24/5);
D = interp(A,I)*(3/4)*dir(dir(A,B));
@D
D = interp(D,E,3/5);
draw(A--I--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(A--D);
label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NE);
label("$E$", E, SE); [/asy>
By the triangle inequality,
\[a + 8 > 13 \implies a > 5,\]where $a$ represents the length of $BC$. It's easy to see that as long as $BC > 5$, there exists a $\triangle ABC$, whose least integral value is $\boxed{6}$.
</think> <answer>6</answer>

